on to Torture, Alan W. Clarke explains how the United States adopted torture as a matter of official policy; how and why it turned to extraordinary rendition as a way to outsource more extreme, mutilating forms of torture; and outlines the steps the United States took to hide its abuses. Many adverse consequences attended American use of torture. False information gleaned from torture was used to justify the Iraq war, adding potency to the charge that the war was illegal under international law. Moreover, European nations and Canada aided, abetted, and became thoroughly enmeshed in U.S.-led torture and renditions, thereby spreading both the problem and the blame for this practice. Clarke offers an extended critique of these activities, placing them in historical and legal context as well as in transnational and comparative perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2020) 0aDeportationxGovernment policyxUnited States. 0aDeportationxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aDetention of personsxGovernment policyxUnited States. 0aDetention of personsxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aExtraordinary renditionxUnited States. 0aExtraordinary renditionzUnited States. 0aExtraordinary rendition. 0aFalse imprisonmentxUnited States. 0aFalse imprisonmentzUnited States. 0aNational securityxUnited States. 0aNational securityzUnited States. 0aTorturexGovernment policyxUnited States. 0aTorturexGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aTorture. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813553122423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813553122.jpg  a978-3-11-0